# 0026. Remove Duplicates from Sorted Array

**Problem Name:** Remove Duplicates from Sorted Array  
**Difficulty:** Easy

---

## Question

Given a sorted integer array `nums`, remove the duplicates **in-place** such that each unique element appears only once. The relative order of the elements should remain the same.

Return the number of unique elements `k`, where the first `k` elements of `nums` contain the unique values.

---

## My Solution

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int removeDuplicates(vector<int>& nums) {
        int k = 1;

        for (int i = 1; i < nums.size(); i++) {
            if (nums[i] != nums[i - 1]) {
                nums[k] = nums[i];
                k++;
            }
        }

        return k;
    }
};
```

---

## Complexity

| Metric | Value |
|--------|-------|
| **Time Complexity** | `O(n)` |
| **Space Complexity** | `O(1)` |

---

## What I Learned

This problem introduced me to the **Two Pointer** technique.

Since the array is already sorted, duplicate elements are always adjacent. Instead of creating a new array, I can overwrite duplicate values by maintaining a pointer that tracks the position of the next unique element.

This helped me understand how in-place array modifications work while keeping the space complexity constant.

---

## Personal Notes

At first, I thought of using another array or a set to store unique values, but that would require extra space.

The key observation was that the array is already sorted, making it possible to solve the problem efficiently with just two pointers.

This problem reinforced an important lesson: **always use the properties of the input (like sorted order) to simplify the solution.**

